-- Indian bonds fall, shares retreat after cbank raises rates
-- By Mumbai markets team
-- Tue Jan 28, 2014 12:44AM EST
-- None



MUMBAI, Jan 28 (Reuters) - Indian government bonds fell on Tuesday, while shares retreated, led by a fall in lenders after the Reserve Bank of India unexpectedly raised interest rates by 25 basis points.

The benchmark 10-year bond yield <IN088323G=CC> rose 8 basis points to 8.79 percent from levels before the RBI decision, bringing the yield up 2 bps on the day. Indian shares fell, with the broader NSE <.NSEI> down 0.4 percent after being up slightly before the decision. Banks led declines, with ICICI Bank Ltd <ICBK.NS> down 2.1 percent.